Picture-Perfect and Full of Energy

This past week, I finally had the chance to visit Vavela Cafe, which lived up to all the beautiful photos I’d seen online. The space is exactly as advertised—bright, modern, and very spacious with plenty of seating. Whether you’re coming solo, with a friend, or in a large group, it’s a welcoming spot with something for everyone.

I was surprised by how busy it was, especially on a rainy day. I expected folks to stay home, but the café had a steady stream of families and remote workers. I came to meet a friend and ended up staying to get some work done afterward. I prefer a calmer café to work in—this one had a lot of movement and distractions.

A heads-up if you’re planning to work here: outlets are limited, and I had several other remote workers come up to me asking if they could use my charger or share the outlet. It’s a place where you’ll want to arrive with your device fully charged.

During my stay, I had an Americano and a toasted croissant, both of which were solid choices. I ended up staying so long that I rolled into lunch and ordered a wildberry hibiscus refresher and a chicken pesto sandwich—both were delicious.

Vavela Cafe is a great choice for casual meetups, brunch, or a lively solo visit. If you’re planning to work, just know it might be a bit too active for deep focus.

Their attention to detail is evident in every cup, whether you’re sipping a classic espresso or trying one of their seasonal specialties.

The coffee itself is exceptional—smooth, bold, and perfectly balanced. You can tell they source their beans with care and know how to bring out the best in them. I was especially impressed by their pour-over, which had incredible depth of flavor and a clean finish.

The space is also thoughtfully designed—cozy yet modern, with plenty of seating and a great vibe for both working or relaxing. Whether you’re a local or just passing through, Vavela Coffee is the kind of place you’ll want to return to again and again. Highly recommended!

Picture-Perfect and Full of Energy

This past week, I finally had the chance to visit Vavela Cafe, which lived up to all the beautiful photos I’d seen online. The space is exactly as advertised—bright, modern, and very spacious with plenty of seating. Whether you’re coming solo, with a friend, or in a large group, it’s a welcoming spot with something for everyone.

I was surprised by how busy it was, especially on a rainy day. I expected folks to stay home, but the café had a steady stream of families and remote workers. I came to meet a friend and ended up staying to get some work done afterward. I prefer a calmer café to work in—this one had a lot of movement and distractions.

A heads-up if you’re planning to work here: outlets are limited, and I had several other remote workers come up to me asking if they could use my charger or share the outlet. It’s a place where you’ll want to arrive with your device fully charged.

During my stay, I had an Americano and a toasted croissant, both of which were solid choices. I ended up staying so long that I rolled into lunch and ordered a wildberry hibiscus refresher and a chicken pesto sandwich—both were delicious.

Vavela Cafe is a great choice for casual meetups, brunch, or a lively solo visit. If you’re planning to work, just know it might be a bit too active for deep focus.
